Recently, I had to look into a few ways to embed a chart into Rails mailer views. Most of the time, I just useÂ chartkickÂ because its simple and easy to use. But in mailers, Chartkick canâ€™t be used directly, so you have to embed an image of the chart for it to work.
After a while, I bumped intoÂ QuickChartÂ an Open Source library to generate chart images by just generating the url with the correct query parameters. And it offers a lot of chart optionsÂ https://quickchart.io/gallery/
https://quickchart.io/chart?c={type:'bar',data:{labels:['Q1','Q2','Q3','Q4'], datasets:[{label:'Users',data:[50,60,70,180]},{label:'Revenue',data:[100,200,300,400]}]}}

And another thing, thereâ€™s also aÂ gemÂ that acts as a Ruby client for QuickChart -https://github.com/typpo/quickchart-ruby
u/chart = QuickChart.new(
  {
    type: 'bar',
    data: {
      labels: ['Q1', 'Q2', 'Q3', 'Q4'],
      datasets: [
        {
          label: 'Users',
          data: [50, 100, 120, 150]
        },
        {
          label: 'Revenue',
          data: [100, 200, 300, 450]
        },
      ]
    },
    options: {
      title: {
        display: true,
        text: 'Users vs Revenue',
        fontSize: 16,
        padding: 16,
      },
    },
  }
)

And then render the URL of that object in your Mailer View.
# apps/views/sample_mailer/sample_email.html.erb

<img src="<%= @chart.get_url %>">



And thatâ€™s it! You can now embed and render charts in your Mailer Views. Very simple and quick to implement.
